  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In 1955, in the sun-drenched towns of Puerto Rico, hundreds of women enrolled in a groundbreaking trial for the birth control pill. They were promised a chance at reproductive freedom, but what they received was far grimmer: dangerously high doses of hormones, undisclosed risks, and side effects so severe that some died without investigation into their deaths (citation unverified).</p>
  <p>The trials weren’t just about testing a drug. They were a manifestation of a historical entanglement between birth control and eugenics—a pseudoscientific movement obsessed with 'improving' humanity through selective breeding. This is a story of autonomy promised and control delivered, a legacy that still haunts reproductive rights today.</p>
</section>
<section id="sanger-eugenic-roots" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Eugenic Roots of Birth Control Advocacy</h2>
  <p>Margaret Sanger, the founder of the American Birth Control League—later Planned Parenthood—didn’t just champion women’s rights. She explicitly tied birth control to eugenic goals, arguing it was a tool for 'weeding out the unfit' and preventing the birth of 'defectives' (citation unverified). Her rhetoric wasn’t a footnote; it was central to her strategy for gaining scientific and social legitimacy in the early 20th century.</p>
  <p>As evidence suggests, she presented birth control as a solution to limit 'unfit' children from 'irresponsible' mothers, blending feminist aims with eugenic reasoning (citation unverified).</p>
  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Birth control was a method for weeding out the unfit." — Margaret Sanger</p></aside>
  <p>Some historians argue Sanger’s eugenic stance was partly strategic, a way to appeal to a hostile, conservative society by framing birth control as a public good rather than a radical feminist demand. Yet, this defense doesn’t erase the intent behind her words or the harm they justified.</p>
</section>
<section id="forced-sterilization" class="reveal">
  <h2>Forced Sterilization: Eugenics in Action</h2>
  <p>The eugenic ideology Sanger endorsed didn’t stay on paper. It became policy. Between 1907 and 1963, over 64,000 to 70,000 individuals in the United States were forcibly sterilized under eugenic laws, often targeting institutionalized women with mental disabilities, as reported in PubMed (2015).</p>
  <p>Marginalized groups bore the brunt. In North Carolina, one of the most aggressive programs sterilized 7,600 women between 1933 and 1973, with roughly 5,000 being African American. An estimated 25% of Indigenous women of child-bearing age faced forced sterilization between 1955 and 1976, per historical records cited in Vertex AI Search (2024).</p>
  <p>These weren’t isolated acts but systemic efforts to control who could reproduce. Historian William Deverell captures the chilling logic: 'If you are sterilizing someone, you are saying… Your possible progeny are inassimilable, and we choose not to deal with that,' as quoted in recent analyses.</p>
</section>
<section id="puerto-rico-trials" class="reveal">
  <h2>Human Experiments in Puerto Rico</h2>
  <p>The 1955 birth control pill trials in Puerto Rico stand as a stark example of eugenic principles applied under the guise of progress. Women, predominantly from impoverished communities, were given doses of oral contraceptives far higher than deemed safe, without full disclosure of risks (citation unverified). Severe side effects were rampant; some deaths went uninvestigated.</p>
  <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
    <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Puerto Rico Trials: The Numbers</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Year:</strong> 1955</li>
      <li><strong>Location:</strong> Puerto Rico</li>
      <li><strong>Dosage:</strong> Significantly higher than safe limits</li>
      <li><strong>Outcome:</strong> Severe side effects, uninvestigated deaths</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p>This wasn’t mere negligence. It reflected a broader pattern of targeting marginalized populations for reproductive experimentation, underpinned by the same eugenic logic that fueled sterilization campaigns. The women of Puerto Rico were not partners in science; they were subjects of control.</p>
</section>
<section id="modern-legacy" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Modern Legacy of Eugenic Thinking</h2>
  <p>Fast forward to 2021: Planned Parenthood publicly denounced Sanger’s eugenic beliefs, with CEO Alexis McGill Johnson stating, 'Margaret Sanger’s racist alliances and belief in eugenics have caused irreparable damage to the health and lives of Black people, Indigenous people, people of color, people with disabilities, immigrants, and many others' (citation unverified). It was an acknowledgment of a tainted foundation.</p>
  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Sanger’s belief in eugenics has caused irreparable damage." — Alexis McGill Johnson, Planned Parenthood CEO</p></aside>
  <p>Yet, the past isn’t neatly buried. Critics like Justice Clarence Thomas argue that Sanger’s ideology still echoes in modern reproductive policies. In his 2019 concurrence in Box v. Planned Parenthood of Indiana and Kentucky, Thomas linked Sanger’s eugenic views to current abortion disparities, noting Black women account for 38% to 42% of reported abortions despite being 13.7% of the female population of childbearing age (citation unverified).</p>
  <p>Defenders of reproductive rights counter that access to birth control and abortion empowers women, especially women of color, to reclaim autonomy—a direct rejection of eugenic control. Michelle Williams of Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health puts it bluntly: 'The eugenics movement has never been about giving women the right to choose… it has been about ripping that autonomy from women deemed inferior,' as cited in recent discussions.</p>
</section>
<section id="tension-autonomy-control" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Tension Between Autonomy and Control</h2>
  <p>Birth control’s history is a paradox: a tool of liberation for some, a weapon of suppression for others. While Sanger and her contemporaries framed their mission as freeing women from unwanted pregnancies, their eugenic rhetoric often targeted specific groups for exclusion from reproduction altogether. The line between choice and coercion blurred.</p>
  <p>Even today, disparities persist. Beyond abortion statistics, coerced sterilizations haven’t vanished—between 2005 and 2011, 148 female prisoners in California were sterilized without required state approvals, as historical data confirms. These incidents raise questions about how much has truly changed.</p>
</section>
<section id="reflection-challenge" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Reflection and a Challenge</h2>
  <p>The birth control movement’s eugenic shadow isn’t just a historical curiosity. It’s a lens through which to view today’s reproductive healthcare disparities—whether in access, outcomes, or trust. How much of the past still shapes who gets care and who gets control?</p>
  <p>This isn’t a question with a tidy answer. It’s a challenge to look closer, to ask whether the systems we celebrate for autonomy might still carry echoes of a darker intent. The evidence demands we keep asking.</p>
</section>
